</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339616" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">RM</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-19T22:56:58+01:00">November 19, 2017 10:56pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Looking forward to this. Thank you. Questions: do you prefer light or dark brown sugar for the sauce, and what metric weight for it, please.  =;&gt;)</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339619" class="comment byuser comment-author-david bypostauthor even depth-2 comdiv bydavid">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">David</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-20T02:06:34+01:00">November 20, 2017 2:06am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comdavid"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%2032%2032'%3E%3C/svg%3E" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" data-lazy-src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" /><noscript><img src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" /></noscript></div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Whoops! When I was publishing this post, my server went down and took a few of the metric conversions with it. I added them back. Thanks!</p>
<p>Also, I tend to prefer light brown sugar for this although dark is fine if you want a stronger flavor and darker color.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339654" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Corine</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-22T14:19:12+01:00">November 22, 2017 2:19pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Splendid. I am making this beauty for Thanksgiving out of town. I don&#8217;t know if the Praline Sauce will travel well. Once cold, I will pour it in a Mason jar. Et voila, on verra!<br />
Happy Thanksgiving, cher David.<br />
(I ordered your new book X 5 so far, and I am just starting&#8230;)</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339663" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Alex in PDX</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-23T00:59:35+01:00">November 23, 2017 12:59am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Is 9&#8243; the correct pan size for the listed cooking time range?  I have one in the oven now, but the 9&#8243; spring-form is filled very close to the top.  This does not seem to match the final thickness I expected based on the glamour shots.  The link for a glass-bottom pan is 10&#8243; which makes me wonder if 10&#8243; was the intended size for the recipe as well?</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339664" class="comment byuser comment-author-david bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 comdiv bydavid">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">David</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-23T01:07:51+01:00">November 23, 2017 1:07am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comdavid"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%2032%2032'%3E%3C/svg%3E" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" data-lazy-src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" /><noscript><img src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" /></noscript></div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Yes, I used a 9-inch springform although I mentioned above (I think) that since most springform pans are made outside the U.S., they are metric so what&#8217;s labeled &#8220;9-inch&#8221; is often slightly larger. (I wrote a variation on this recipe for a <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/spiced-pumpkin-cheesecake-with-caramel-bourbon-sauce-233179" rel="nofollow">magazine</a> a number of years ago, that has a great test kitchen, and they found it worked well in a 9-inch pan.) </p>
<p>Because <a href="http://i.ebayimg.com/00/s/MTYwMFgxMTk1/z/ElUAAOSwPCVX7rpl/$_12.JPG?set_id=880000500F" rel="nofollow">the pan I use</a> isn&#8217;t made any longer, I linked to that one (which is slightly larger, and inexpensive), which will work just fine.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339665" class="comment even thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Robert O&#8217;Sullivan</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-23T06:12:25+01:00">November 23, 2017 6:12am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Although we don&#8217;t celebrate Thanksgiving in Australia, and use of pumpkin in desserts generally earns one a few sideways glances, as soon as I saw this recipe I knew I had to try it &#8211; and boy am I glad I did! A-mazing! I usually find baked cheesecakes quite stodgy, but the filling in this is something else &#8211; so light and delicious. Speculoos biscuits worked perfectly for the base. And that sauce! Oh my lordy!!! I will just have to try it swirled through vanilla ice-cream. Another great recipe, David.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339677" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Desiree</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-24T03:59:43+01:00">November 24, 2017 3:59am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>H David, made this pie today for Thanksgiving.  Followed the recipe to a T, lined the outside of the pan, put in water bath in oven for 70 mins and let it rest in the water bath for 30 mins after we took it out.  Left in fridge over night. The outside looked gorgeous and firm, but when we cut into it today, the middle/inside was unmanageably soft and gooey.  It was impossible to cut a piece, since the inside part just sort of poured out. Tasted great but was not very pretty and ended up everywhere :/ Not sure where I went wrong.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339684" class="comment byuser comment-author-david bypostauthor even depth-2 comdiv bydavid">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">David</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-24T16:42:01+01:00">November 24, 2017 4:42pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comdavid"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%2032%2032'%3E%3C/svg%3E" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" data-lazy-src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" /><noscript><img src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" /></noscript></div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Sound to me like your oven may be off. (I keep a thermometer in mine to make sure it&#8217;s accurate.) Other commenters &#8211; Robert O, Michael, + Jon, reported it came out well for them.</p>
<p>(People also liked it on <a href="https://www.epicurious.com/recipes/food/views/spiced-pumpkin-cheesecake-with-caramel-bourbon-sauce-233179" rel="nofollow">Epicurious</a> so I&#8217;d say your oven might be the culprit.)</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339680" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Michael Y.</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-24T07:13:10+01:00">November 24, 2017 7:13am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Hey David. Thanks for the excellent recipe made this for Thanksgiving today and people really enjoyed it.</p>
<p>I did forget to pre bake the crust by accident but it turned out alright anyways&#8230; perhaps a bit less crisp then if I had remembered to bake it but certainly didn&#8217;t ruin anything. I also used spekuloos (sp?) cookies from Trader Joes instead of graham crackers. </p>
<p>I didn&#8217;t have a glass bottom springform pan so I just use a regular all-metal springform and that worked out fine. Just had to be careful not to scratch the interior when I was cutting the cheese cake.</p>
<p>I didn&#8217;t have a big enough roasting pan for the water bath so I put it in a large cast iron skillet and that worked out fine. </p>
<p>People also loved the bourbon sauce!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339687" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Theresa smith</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-24T17:25:27+01:00">November 24, 2017 5:25pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>David, I made this Pumpkin Cheesecake for Thanksgiving dinner yesterday.  It turned out beautifully.  I cooked it for an hour 10 min. Firm and very silky.  Thanks for the recipe!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339690" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Lisa Lewis</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-24T18:54:01+01:00">November 24, 2017 6:54pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>I made this for Thanksgiving at my sister&#8217;s house last night. I was told to bring &#8220;only pie&#8221; but I had to make this too. It was a huge hit&#8230;truly delicious. Definitely a recipe I&#8217;ll add to my repertoire.  I used a biscoff cookie crust, which was perfect. And the praline sauce! No words.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339692" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Lisa Huff</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-24T22:02:00+01:00">November 24, 2017 10:02pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Yum Yum Yum! Looks delicious!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339707" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Anita Iaconangelo</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-27T11:26:37+01:00">November 27, 2017 11:26am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Wow! I made this and it turned out great! The bourbon sauce was really decadent, and if that weren&#8217;t enough, I had a bowl of whipped cream to dollop on top of the warm sauce.  Made this for Thanksgiving in Italy with 18 international guests and it was a big hit with all.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339720" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Martinn Key2paris</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-27T19:06:01+01:00">November 27, 2017 7:06pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Had my Thanksgiving lunch yesterday. Made my usual mini cheesecakes with orange zest this time and served them with your praline pecan sauce. They love it !!! I&#8217;ll keep the recipe for the years to come as I am sure it will become a classsic.  Also served a trio of homemade ice creams (speculos from Dandoi in Brussels, gingerbread, maple syrup and roasted pecan)  I used a real vanilla bean. Merci for the praline sauce</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339729" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Jeff Rose</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-11-27T21:43:30+01:00">November 27, 2017 9:43pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>I made this for Thanksgiving and it was fantastic! I baked it for 1 hour and ten minutes. I made the crust from &#8220;Biscoff&#8221; brand speculoos cookies. This was my first time making cheesecake and it came out great. I used a plastic serving utensil to keep from scratching the bottom of the pan when serving. The sauce was outstanding and the small amount leftover very easy to reheat the next day. THANK YOU for such a great recipe David!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339798" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Alene</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-01T17:52:49+01:00">December 1, 2017 5:52pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>I have a very similar recipe in a Nov, 1990 issue of Gourmet, and it uses 3 lg eggs.  What will 4 eggs do to the cheesecake?  The key ingredients are the same.  I remember making it with 3 eggs twice, and it is very light and wobbly.  Yours looks more dense.<br />
Could it be the amt of the eggs?  Thank you!<br />
Happy Chanukah&#8230; soon!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339799" class="comment odd alt thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Connie</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-01T18:10:12+01:00">December 1, 2017 6:10pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Hi David:</p>
<p>I made this and it turned out fantastic! I tweaked the crust (used the Simply Recipes version with pecans and used gingersnaps instead of graham crackers) and made your caramel sauce instead of the praline sauce. </p>
<p>I will add that while it’s likely my oven temp, I noticed the middle was still quite loose after an hour and 15 minutes, so I baked for another 30-45 minutes before turning the oven off and letting it cool inside with the door propped open for an hour or so before letting it cool on the counter.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339817" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Alene</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-02T22:19:56+01:00">December 2, 2017 10:19pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Hi.  I made your sauce with the cheesecake.  Yours looked thicker than mine.  Way thicker!  I ended up taking a little cornstarch diluted with the sauce.  It did thicken more, but yours looks seriously better than mine.  Tastes good though, yummy even!  I&#8217;m wondering if I didn&#8217;t let the caramel cook long enough before you add the rest of the ingredients.  Oh well, it&#8217;s going to the party with imperfect sauce.  Thank you!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339821" class="comment byuser comment-author-david bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 comdiv bydavid">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">David</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-03T18:26:52+01:00">December 3, 2017 6:26pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comdavid"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%2032%2032'%3E%3C/svg%3E" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" data-lazy-src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" /><noscript><img src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" /></noscript></div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>The sauce will thicken if let to sit. So you could make it in advance, but it can also be cooked a bit further, until it&#8217;s almost as thick as you&#8217;d like, but it&#8217;s hard to tell when it&#8217;s still warm how thick it&#8217;ll be, once it cools down.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339858" class="comment even thread-even depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Sharon</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-05T18:57:21+01:00">December 5, 2017 6:57pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>I plan to make the sauce as Christmas gifts.  It was fabulous!  Must it be refrigerated?  Could it be canned in a water bath?</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339859" class="comment byuser comment-author-david bypostauthor odd alt depth-2 comdiv bydavid">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">David</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-05T19:54:23+01:00">December 5, 2017 7:54pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comdavid"><img src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%2032%2032'%3E%3C/svg%3E" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" data-lazy-src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" /><noscript><img src="https://www.davidlebovitz.com/wp-content/themes/davidlebovitz/images/dl.svg" width="32" height="32" alt="David Lebovitz" /></noscript></div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>I think you could leave it out of the refrigerator for a certain period of time, but I would store it in the refrigerator if it&#8217;s not going to be used that day, or maybe the next. I&#8217;ve not canned it but you can check here for <a href="http://nchfp.uga.edu/how/can_home.html" rel="nofollow">guidelines on canning</a> and see if they offer up a method or technique.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339860" class="comment even depth-3 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Sharon</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-05T22:39:55+01:00">December 5, 2017 10:39pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Thanks, I&#8217;ll check it out.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
<ul class="children">
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-339864" class="comment odd alt depth-4 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Sharon</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2017-12-06T04:28:44+01:00">December 6, 2017 4:28am</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>After researching this question, I&#8217;ve concluded that one cannot water-bath can caramel sauce.  The product is not acidic enough to kill off botulism spores.  It may be possible to pressure can it, but it is not recommended for the home cook.  So, best to eat it up or freeze it for longer term storage.</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment-li">
		<article id="comment-456224" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 comdiv">
			<div class="commeta">
				<ul>
					<li class="comauth">Nicole</li>
					<li class="comdate"><time datetime="2024-11-22T16:47:53+01:00">November 22, 2024 4:47pm</time></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
						<div class="comright">
				<div class="comcontent notop nobot">
										<p>Hi David! My copy of perfect scoop is tattered and stained in all the best ways! I found the receipt tucked into one of the pages the other day, it’s from a little local bookstore in 2009!<br />
I tried to add this comment on an ice cream post but wasn&#8217;t able to… I have two questions…sometimes, the cream is split and half goes into the cooking custard, sometimes none of it (like the eggnog). What is the deciding factor on how much of the cream is put into the custard?<br />
If could go back in time and know that I was literally gonna be making hundreds of batches, I would’ve bought a self freezing machine. I’ve been using my original Cuisinart since I started making ice cream. It’s the most basic one, I have four freezer bowls that I keep in the freezer at alll times. Is it worth upgrading to a self freezing machine? Is the ice cream better? Feels like if I’m gonna do that might as well go all the way to the breville, any thoughts on the differences between the self freezing Cuisinart or breville?<br />
Ok one more… instead of an ice bath do you ever just put the remaining cup of cream in the freezer for 30 min or so ahead of time so it cools the custard quickly?<br />
Thanks in advance for your time. Can’t tell you the joy that this ice cream from your book has brought to me and all my friends and family. This year I’m doing a 24 flavor 4 ounce cup advent calendar of ice cream!</p>
				</div>
				<div class="comactions">
					<ul>
											</ul>
				</div>
			</div>
		</article>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		</ul>

			</div>

	
	
</div>

					</div>
				</footer>

			</div>
			</div>

			<div id="sidebar" class="clearfix">
